# Senior JavaScript Standards

- Write clean, minimal JavaScript and TypeScript that is easy for any team member to read.
- Prefer simple control flow, explicit names, and small functions over clever or overly abstract constructs.
- Reuse existing local patterns and helpers before introducing new abstractions.
- Keep the main priority in every change: less code, less duplication, and simpler behavior.

# Reuse And Utilities

- Do not duplicate logic when the same behavior appears in multiple places.
- Extract small utilities for repeated code only when it clearly reduces duplication or improves readability.
- Keep utilities focused and colocated with nearby code unless the repo already has a shared location for that concern.

# eve And Slack

- Before changing eve behavior, read the relevant installed docs from `node_modules/eve/docs/` when available; otherwise use `https://eve.dev/docs/introduction` and `https://vercel.com/eve`.
- Preserve eve's filesystem-first architecture: instructions, tools, channels, connections, subagents, schedules, and shared libraries should stay in their expected directories.
- Keep Slack channel code inside `agent/channels/` focused on Slack integration concerns; avoid mixing channel glue with core agent logic unless the existing architecture requires it.
- Keep authored prompt constants in `agent/lib/prompts/{feature}-prompt.ts`; do not add unsupported agent-root directories like `agent/prompts/`.
- Write editable prompt constants as multiline template literals so they read like markdown, instead of arrays of joined strings.

# Working Style

- Ask a clarifying question when a requirement is ambiguous or when multiple implementations would change the result meaningfully.
- Do not make changes the user did not ask for.
- Keep edits scoped, conservative, and aligned with the surrounding codebase.
